replyContent: Hi Phillip, the two of us are very proud of Agent A, we worked sleepless nights for over a year to bring out ch5 as a free update which arrived in Aug 2019 capping off 6 years of hard work. We've honestly never been more passionate and worked harder on a project in our lives. We're sorry to disappoint and realise it's not for everyone.

I wish I could give half stars. The game has great graphics, nice audio / music and it has a good story line. The puzzles are generally on the easy side, which is welcome, as I don't mind a bit of thinking, but sometimes, games make puzzles so obscure. However, it loses marks for the back / forth tedium on every level. It feels like one step forwards and two steps backwards every time. And it loses another star for having colour based puzzles in it. If you're colour blind like I am, then you will need help in a few of the puzzles. Oh, and you'll need to take a lot of pictures of your screen or write a lot of stuff down, there's no way people are going to remember that much info. Overall, it's fun, but the flaws are glaring and severely detract from the experience.

replyContent: Hi Shadi, we're sorry you've had issues with requiring a net connection. We take part in Google's Play Pass which requires us to check the license, it's out of our hands on how this works, it's certainly not our intention to treat you badly. We agree with you regarding piracy, it's not why it's there, we have passed on your feedback, thank you.

Awesome! I love how this puzzle adventure genre is evolving, and this game is the perfect example. Graphics are beautiful and animations are very smooth, and when you press some button and everything in the room turns and you get some secret room stuff, whoa! super cool. Puzzles are fun, challenging without being overly difficult, and always quite logic so you won't be complaining for not-intuitive things as it happens in other games. No 'pixel hunting' though you need to find some small blueprints for example, but they're always clear to see. The story is very cool, and I specially love the humor touch they've added, with all the secret spy references. I'm through the 5th chapter right now, and I already want more games from this developer in the future, hopefully more on this saga. Totally recommended game!

replyContent: Hi there, sorry about this, but the license check result is unavoidable, we wish we could remove but that's out of our control I'm afraid. But fyi, the result is cached for 30 days and then every time you open the app with a net connection it will reset the 30 day counter. So in most case it only needs to check once before a long flight.

Edit: Turns out I was a dumb ass. I was taping instead of swiping on the interface. The developer was a wonderful help and responded to my emails. I sent him a video and he found the issue immediately.   I'm changing this review to 5 stars because it is a wonderful game. Clever and just the right level of difficult. I frustratingly did have to google a few things, but mostly it was face palm stuff.  Original review is as follows:  I'm using a pixelbook and the symbols on the letterbox (where you use the  card to access it) are frozen. I can hear the click, but there is no  animation/image change. I think this is blocking me from progressing in the  game. Chromebooks are becoming increasingly more used for android apps. It  really should be vetted out on that platform. I will happily change this  review if fixed or I'm shown to be being stupid.

This is, by far, the best video game I've ever played. I first discovered  it on Apple TV, and our entire family got into it. Our 6 year old twin boys  and 8 year old girl were completely engrossed, and worked together to  figure it out. It was the best online, family gaming experience ever! The  graphics are gorgeous, with a sort of mid-century modern Madmen aesthetic.  The story is compelling. And we loved the puzzles and logic games and  especially the game's sense of humor and amusing references. Our only  frustrations are that the next chapters never seem to come out quickly  enough, and it has spoiled us for any other games. I have searched and  searched and have yet to find its equal. Thank you for creating such a  beautiful, thoughtfully created game that draws us in, challenges, amuses  and surprises us. It is a joy to find this treasure amidst the sea of dreck  out there. Please hurry up and come out with chapter 5, and if it is indeed  the final chapter, please make other similar games soon! Your eternal fans,  Melissa, Amanda, Morgan(now 9 and pestering me to write you to encourage you to release chapter 5 already), Asher & Nathaniel (now 7)

This game kept me hooked for hours. It's the best mobile game I've played 
recently. Everything about it is top notch. The visuals are pretty basic 
but it still look beautiful. The music really gives you the feeling of a 
detective. The story - you play as an agent/detective in pursuit of a spy, 
and the chase is quite interesting. The dialogs are well written and even 
funny at times. The puzzles are neither tough nor easy. Some require a 
little patience but it mostly involves backtracking, and there is always 
something new to discover when you head back. Puzzles combined with the 
music, and you are in for a treat. Also this game has some of the smoothest 
animations I have seen in a mobile game. Worth every penny. Great job Yak & 
Co. Can't wait for the next chapter. And maybe a sequelüòÅ

As a fan of the Room series, I am always on the lookout for something close 
once I complete their latest offering (usually in just a day or two). That 
is why I searched around and came across Agent A. I like the fairly 
creative and difficult enough puzzle aspects, as well as the depth of each 
level. This is the first time I've played the game, and finished all 4 
levels in a couple of days. Had to do a couple online searches for 2 parts 
I got stuck on, but quite honestly this ended up being due to what I 
considered minor game flaws, as opposed to my inability to solve those 
issues. The graphics could be better with a lot more detail and depth 
(again, spoiled by the Room series). Also, I think my biggest pet peeve is 
how the movement of the character works when moving, or examining an object 
- way too linear - I like the Room games style much better where it feels 
like you're walking and when you reach an object, you can navigate around 
it as opposed to just being fixed in position much more fluid and natural. 
If you are a fan of the Room games I think you will like this as a somewhat 
lower level alternative. It sounds like they release one chapter at a time. 
I will probably buy the next chapter when it comes out, but wish they would 
do 4 or 5 chapters at a time given how quickly I was able to navigate 
through the current 4. Honestly, if I had purchased Chapter 1 when it came 
out and that was all I got, I probably would have never purchased any 
subsequent chapters one at a time.

gratifying when solved. (You don't need to use the 'tape' on a

art style, and 50's (or 60's?) spy vibe and you got a great game. 5 out of 
5.

Overall, this game is well done. The visuals are lovely, the music is thematic, and the story, while thin, is juuuust interesting enough to keep me going.   Which is good, because one of the main things I don't like about this game is how incredibly tedious it is to actually solve the puzzles owing to the amount of backtracking required. I realize this is standard with escape games, but the sheer number of rooms and positions *within* those rooms one must navigate to get anything done is frustrating. By Part 3 I was wishing for a warp feature of some kind to at least trim some of the time required to physically travel around the house.  The second thing I wish this game had is a hint system. I don't need answers spoon fed to me, but even something as simple as "have you looked at [object] more closely?" would have put me back on the right track at a few points when I couldn't see the way forward.  Other than that, this is a straightforward but fun game. I recommend it to anyone who's looking to kill some time on a few puzzles.

If you like puzzle games, you'll love this one. With a humorous dialogue and various allusions to James Bond, this game will keep you engaged and using your brain to progress through the story. The puzzles are fresh and logical, and though some may be slightly challenging to certain people, nobody should have such a problem with them to need to cheat or receive hints. I found some puzzles to be too easy, but the majority of them were straightforward and still made me think. One of the joys of a great puzzle game is coming across those rare puzzles that make me smile and think "Wow, that was very clever!" This game has quite a few puzzles like that.  Aside from the puzzles, the controls are ridiculously easy and rarely did I encounter a problem. The artwork is gorgeous; I absolutely love this style of drawing and animation! It's just all-around a fantastic game, and worth how much it costs, and then some. Seriously, if you don't usually buy games, go out on a limb and buy this one. If you do, know that your money was well spent!

The permissions (and nagging to rate, like, or tip them) are few and far between. Honestly, it's the best game (on Android) that I have ever played. Can't wait for chapter 5! The graphics are a cartoon stylised version of the James Bond Dr No mid century modern vibe with suitably jazzy music to match & voices and sound fx appropriately fitting to the spy thriller genre. The puzzles were challenging for me in a fun way, not easy & boring, or frustratingly over the top difficult. The story is simple & predictable, but it provides a logical framework for the puzzles to exist in. The controls all work fine except for the 2 finger pinch to move out or back, which quite often results in going in exactly the opposite direction, forwards. All the game chapters are not available yet, but once you have paid you do not have to pay for further instalments. I don't regret paying for this game, I've  enjoyed it so far (except for the pinch control glitch) & look forward to the next chapter.

There are good things about this game if you like the genre, in that it's intricate with solvable puzzles (usually). The graphics are usually very clear, unlike The Room Two which is so dark as to be almost unplayable during the daytime. The big negative for me is how slowly each room or closeup loads, some in particular being extremely slow (the house entrance wth the fish tank for example). If you find you need to go from outside back in and up to the third floor of the house, which is not an infrequent occurrence, it takes foreeeever. I am uninstalling for this reason alone - it really is a deal breaker.
